Predicting weight at birth based on US Birth data

Course Title - PCAM ZC321¶

Problem Statement¶

Low birth weight (LBW) of an infant can have serious health effects on it in its later life. World Health Organization defines Low birth weight (LBW) as a birth weight of an infant weighing 2,499 g or less. The birth weight of a baby is notable because very low birth weight babies are 100 times more likely to die compared to normal birth weight babies. We have to predict the weight of a baby

# Listing unique value counts in each feature

def getUniqueValues(data):
    colNames = data.columns
    listUnique = []
    for col in colNames:
        listUnique.append([col, data[col].nunique()])

    d1 = pd.DataFrame(listUnique)
    d1.columns = ['Feature Name', 'Unique Value']
    d1 = d1.sort_values(by='Unique Value', ascending=False)
    return d1

getUniqueValues(birthdata)

# Checking for any single value columns and dropping them
def removeSingleValueColumns(data):
    d1 = data.copy()
    for col in d1.columns:
        if d1[col].nunique() == 1:
            d1 = d1.drop([col], axis=1)
    return d1

birthdata=removeSingleValueColumns(birthdata)

# Define function to visualize the count
def GraphMissingValueCount(data):
    missingCount = data.isnull().sum()
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
    plt.xticks(np.arange(len(missingCount)) + 0.5, missingCount.index, rotation='vertical')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.bar(np.arange(len(missingCount)), missingCount)
    plt.show()

#help us determine that a particular feature is categorical in nature.

In [37]:
maxi = 10 #threshold value
catcolumns = []
numColumns=[]
for i in featureset:
    if birthdata[i].nunique() < maxi:
        catcolumns.append(i)
    else:
        numColumns.append(i)

# function to replace NAN values with mean value

def meanImpute(DataFrame,ColName):
   
     mean=DataFrame[ColName].mean()
    
    # replace nan values with most occured category
     DataFrame[ColName].fillna(mean,inplace=True)
In [40]:

# function to replace NAN values with mode value

def modeImpute(DataFrame,ColName):

     mode=DataFrame[ColName].mode()[0]
    
    # replace nan values with most occured category
     DataFrame[ColName].fillna(mode,inplace=True)

#In order to further use the data in outlier detection convert object fields to numerical

#Define the function to perform encoding
def func_labelEncoder(data, columns):
    d1 = data.copy()
    for i in columns:
        le = LabelEncoder()
        d1[i] = le.fit_transform(d1[i])
    return d1

def func_minMaxScaler(data):
    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    dfScaled = scaler.fit_transform(data)
    dfScaled = pd.DataFrame(dfScaled, columns=data.columns)
    return dfScaled

Detecting the Outliers Using IQR¶

In [55]:
for col_name in dfScaled.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns[:]:
    print(col_name)
    q1 = dfScaled[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = dfScaled[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    
    low = q1-1.5*iqr
    high = q3+1.5*iqr
    print("Outliers = ",dfScaled.loc[(dfScaled[col_name] < low) | (dfScaled[col_name] > high), col_name])

# calculating gestation weeks value from exixitng  DLMP_MM and DOB_MM features
def func_GestWk(row):
    dob_mm=row['DOB_MM']
    dlmp_mm=row['DLMP_MM']
    
    if dob_mm < dlmp_mm:dob_mm=dob_mm+12 # adding 12 to handle next year
    noOfMonth=dob_mm-dlmp_mm
    week=0
    week=int(noOfMonth*4)
    return week
In [60]:

# Spearman's rank correlation to visualize the co-relation with the target variable DBWT

def func_spearman(df, column):
    data = pd.DataFrame()
    data['column'] = column
    data['spearman'] = [df[f].corr(df['DBWT'], 'spearman') for f in column]
    data = data.sort_values('spearman')
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 20))
    sns.barplot(data=data, y='column', x='spearman', orient='h')
    return 
feat = birthdata.columns 
func_spearman(birthdata, feat)

# Binning the data for all numeric columns
def func_createBin(df, cols, no=4):
    d1 = df.copy()
    for i in cols[1:len(cols)]:
        bins = np.linspace(d1[i].min(), d1[i].max(), no)
        d1[i + "Bin"] = pd.cut(d1[i], bins, precision=1, include_lowest=True, right=True)

    return d1

binCol=birthdata.columns
df_bin=func_createBin(birthdata, binCol, no=4)

# Perform the model evaluation on test data
def ModelEvaluation(testData, predData):
    print("Mean squared error(MSE) = %.2f" %   mean_squared_error(testData, predData))
    print("Root Mean squared error(RMSE) = %.2f" % math.sqrt(  mean_squared_error(testData, predData)))
    print('Mean Absolute Error:', metrics.mean_absolute_error(testData, predData))
    print('R squared = %.2f' % r2_score(testData, predData))
    
    return r2_score(testData, predData)

Model with outlier imputation¶

In [108]:
#imputing outliers with median

for col_name in df.select_dtypes(include=np.number).columns[:]:
    print(col_name)
    q1 = df[col_name].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df[col_name].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3 - q1
    
    low = q1-1.5*iqr
    high = q3+1.5*iqr 
    print("Change the outliers with median ",df[col_name].median())
    df.loc[(df[col_name] < low) | (df[col_name] > high), col_name] = df[col_name].median()
